me":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Balweary was born in 1235, in Bow of Fife, Fife, Scotland as the daughter of Sir Richard Balweary - Baron of Balweary, Knight. She had at least 3 sons with Sir Michael Scott Second Lord of Balwearie. She died in Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, and was buried in Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1235–":"1235–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1249–1304":"1249–1304","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1228":"1228","1304":"1304","1249":"1249","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1265":"1265","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1294":"1294","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Bow of Fife, Fife, Scotland":"Bow of Fife, Fife, Scotland","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fifeshire, Scotland.":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1235–":"1235–Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1249–1304":"1249–1304","1265–1294":"1265–1294","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1275–1330":"1275–1330","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1304":"1304","1249":"1249","1235":"1235","1268":"1268","1265":"1265","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1294":"1294","Balwearie Castle, Kirkcaldy, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kirkcaldy, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kirkcaldy, Fife, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bow of Fife, Fife, Scotland":"Bow of Fife, Fife, Scotla